<paragraph id="2D2A36B0FF9EFFA9FCBDAE67FC13FB5E" blockId="7.[810,1420,842,1527]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="1FE1EAA2FF9EFFA9FCBDAE67FC28FBF5" bold="true" box="[810,971,1055,1079]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Identification.</emphasis>
This is a large cat with a long tail and no spots. The head and ears are small and rounded. The dorsal color is reddish brown, and the underparts are whitish (
<bibRefCitation id="49044B41FF9EFFA9FCC0AEFCFC07FB5E" author="Currier MJP" box="[855,996,1156,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref9759" refString="Currier MJP (1983) Felis concolor. Mammalian Species 1983: 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3503951" type="journal article" year="1983">Currier 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="658F653BFF9EFFA9FCBDAED3FB1BFAEA" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2D2A36B0FF9EFFA9FCBDAED3FB1BFAEA" blockId="7.[810,1420,842,1527]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="1FE1EAA2FF9EFFA9FCBDAED3FC5DFB01" bold="true" box="[810,958,1195,1219]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Distribution.</emphasis>
Central, southwestern 
<collectingCountry id="55827620FF9EFFA9FB45AED3FAC4FB01" box="[1234,1319,1195,1219]" name="Canada" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Canada</collectingCountry>
; central, northwest 
<collectingCountry id="55827620FF9EFFA9FC36AEB5FC3BFB27" box="[929,984,1229,1253]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">USA</collectingCountry>
, through most of 
<collectingCountry id="55827620FF9EFFA9FB39AEB5FAE3FB27" box="[1198,1280,1229,1253]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to southern South America (
<bibRefCitation id="49044B41FF9EFFA9FC4DAE96FB84FAC5" author="Currier MJP" box="[986,1127,1262,1287]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref9759" refString="Currier MJP (1983) Felis concolor. Mammalian Species 1983: 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3503951" type="journal article" year="1983">Currier 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Recorded habitats in 
<collectingRegion id="EF51F852FF9EFFA9FACCAE96FC9BFAEA" country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
are quebradas, sierras, and valleys.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="658F653BFF9EFFA9FCBDAF4FFC24FA35" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2D2A36B0FF9EFFA9FCBDAF4FFC24FA35" blockId="7.[810,1420,842,1527]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="1FE1EAA2FF9EFFA9FCBDAF4FFC7AFA8D" bold="true" box="[810,921,1335,1359]" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="EA954D33FF9EFFA9FC30AF40FC06FA8D" authorityName="Jardine" authorityYear="1834" box="[935,997,1336,1359]" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Puma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Puma</taxonomicName>
is the second largest felid in 
<collectingCountry id="55827620FF9EFFA9FAC4AF40FCAEFAB3" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, second only to Jaguar, 
<taxonomicName id="EA954D33FF9EFFA9FBFFAF21FC85FA50" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Panthera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="676" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="onca">
<emphasis id="1FE1EAA2FF9EFFA9FBFFAF21FAE8FAB2" box="[1128,1291,1369,1393]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Panthera onca</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
. Based on current records for 
<collectingRegion id="EF51F852FF9EFFA9FB20AF02FACEFA50" box="[1207,1325,1402,1426]" country="Mexico" name="Chihuahua" pageId="7" pageNumber="676">Chihuahua</collectingRegion>
(López- González and García-Mendoza 2012), both species are not sympatric because Jaguar records are restricted to the quebradas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
